<br>
Kanji was originally developped by the Chinese for their own language (called 'Hanzi' in Chinese). You can read a great history of its formation at <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://<br>
http://www.kanjigraphy.com/mainpages/info/history.html"><br>
http://www.kanjigraphy.com/mainpages/info/history.html</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> . The most important thing to remember though is that around 80% of kanji is composed of a 'root' element and a 'phonetic' element. Take for example the kanji 飯 which means meal. The left side is the 'root' element (食) which expresses the idea of eating. The right side is the 'phonetic' element (反） which expresses the sound 'han'. Other kanji which include the 食 root are 飲 and 館 , which mean 'drink' and 'place to eat' (although the latter has acquired other meanings too). The kanjis 版、板、販、坂、all have the same 'han' sound in them.<br>
<br>
 Of course, after thousands of years of evolution in China, a lot of exceptions have developped. Add in the fact that the Japanese twisted the look and/or pronounciation of many kanji for another 1500 years and what we have today is a writing system as cumbersome as English spelling, only with thousands of kanji instead of 26 letters.<br>
<br>
 This doesn't mean that the language is impossible to learn. It's just that it will require a greater amount of time and effort compared to most other languages to achieve fluency. I wish you good luck in your study. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC>  <td colspan="2">  <table width="100%" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="5">   <tr>    <td valign="top" align="left" width="255"><script language='JavaScript' type='text/javascript'><!--   if (!document.phpAds_used) document.phpAds_used = ',';   phpAds_random = new String (Math.random()); phpAds_random = phpAds_random.substring(2,11);     document.write ("<" + "script language='JavaScript' type='text/javascript' src='");   document.write ("http://ads.ezboard.com/adjs.php?n=" + phpAds_random);   document.write ("&amp;what=zone:92&amp;target=_blank");   document.write ("&amp;exclude=" + document.phpAds_used);   if (document.referer)      document.write ("&amp;referer=" + escape(document.referer));   document.write ("'><" + "/script>");//--></script><noscript><a href='http://ads.ezboard.com/adclick.php?n=a297c98c' target='_blank'><img src='http://ads.ezboard.com/adview.php?what=zone:92&amp;n=a297c98c' border='0' alt=''></a></noscript>    </td>   </tr>  </table> </td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sethness>SethNess</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.fureai-ch.ne.jp/~seth/clearhappy.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/14/03 5:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p084.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1224.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> pens and kanji</span><hr size=1> Yes, knowing the &quot;parts&quot; of Kanji will help you to <br>
1) understand<br>
2) write and<br>
3) pronounce<br>
Kanji that you're just-now learning.<br>
<br>
(Those &quot;parts&quot;, by the way, are called &quot;radicals&quot; usually, and sometimes called &quot;elements&quot;.)<br>
<br>
Sometimes the relationship between a Kanji's meaning, and the radicals used to write it, will seem totally off-base to us.  But, the point is, you're having to learn only to recognize the presence of a couple of radicals that you already know.  That's a hell of alot easier than trying to learn a Kanji that contains nothing you recognize.<br>
<br>
Try to use &quot;image training&quot; and telling yourself a little story, to make the kanji more memorable.  For example, the Kanji for 6 looks a little like the kanji for BIG, and both look like a little person spreading his arms and legs really wide.  Try to imagine (and repeat to yourself) that the man is telling a fish-story:  &quot;I caught a fish that was THIIIIIIIS BIG !  6 feet wide !!!&quot;<br>
<br>
For another example, the kanji for &quot;food/eat&quot; (mentioned elsewhere in this thread) is the kanji for &quot;good&quot; (<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>yoi</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->)  with a little roof over it.  WHY ?  Darned if I know.  But if you tell yourself &quot;It's GOOD EATING under THIS ROOF&quot;, and imagine some guy at Howard Johnson's restaurant (Denny's, Mickey D's, Wendy's, etc...) with an exaggerated roof, then you're well on your way to remembering those Kanji.<br>
<br>
Naturally, it's therefore alot easier on YOU if you learn Kanji in related groups (say, all the characters that contain the radical for &quot;good&quot;).  A book that can help alot with this kind of study ... and recognizing the radicals ... is KANJI Pict-O-Graphix: Mnemonics for Japanese Kanji by Michael Rowley .  Here's a link to it at Amazon.com. <br>
 <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/0962813702/qid=1063589955/sr=1-1/ref=sr_1_1/002-4990448-1187229?v=glance&s=books">www.amazon.com/exec/obido...ce&s=books</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END-->  <br>
<br>
It's $15 bucks VERY well spent.<br>
<br>
To learn Katakana (or refresh your memory about Hiragana), check out one of my home-pages:<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.fureai-ch.ne.jp/~seth/hiragana1.html">www.fureai-ch.ne.jp/~seth/hiragana1.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
They're packed with cute illustrations to make Japanese memorable.<br>
=====<br>
You asked about special pens to write in Kanji.  Yes, there are special pens.  In English, they're called &quot;Brush Pens&quot;.  In Japanese, they're called &quot;fude pens&quot; or just &quot;fude&quot;.  You can get ones that are just very pointy, round-brush pens that you have to dip in India Ink, OR you can get nifty ones that are basically magic markers with long, pointy, very soft, round points.<br>
<br>
The technique for holding them, and drawing with them, is RADICALLY different from what we Western-style calligraphers prefer.  For example, a Western-style calligrapher holds his pen at a 45-degree angle or so, and uses a pen-tip that's shaped like a chisel:  thin one way, wide another way. Asian calligraphers, on the other hand, try to hold their pens straight up'n'down, and spend alot of time worrying about the order in which strokes are written, and the shape of the ENDS of each stroke. <br>
<br>
This is more a matter of prettiness than of telling two similar kanji apart.  <br>
<br>
Interesting side-note:  Japanese cartoonists deliberately chose to go for lettering-styles that ignore the shapes of the ends of each stroke.  This became so prevalent amongst Japanese cartoon-magazines that kanji where the ends of the strokes all look alike are called &quot;MANGA-STYLE&quot; in Japanese.  (Manga = comic book, in Japanese) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gunyouken>gunyouken</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/19/03 1:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p084.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1224.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: pens and kanji</span><hr size=1> <br>
