<br>
I have heard that learning Chinese is much easier for English speaking people because the Chinese grammar is quite similar to English, which is 'Subject + Verb + Object pattern'.  Also they communicate with people in a definite manner. 'Yes' means YES and 'No' means NO.<br>
<br>
Most of the Japanese people do not answer definitely.<br>
For example;<br>
A: Okashi meshiagari masuka? (Would you like some candies?)<br>
B: Iie kekkou desu. (No, thank you.) <br>
<br>
In this case, A needs to ask B if he wants some AGAIN because B's first 'No, thank you' is just a social language. 'No' does not mean NO.<br>
Therefore the next dialogue will be....<br>
<br>
A: Dozo enryo nasarazuni. (Please feel free to take some.)<br>
B: Sou desuka. Dewa itadaki masu. (Well then, I will have some.)<br>
